Date:  0/0/1930
Source:  Early Canterbury Runs
Author:  ACLAND
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote:  To hunt sheep off the higher parts of their winter country onto lower, safer [land] when snow is expected; e.g., `We hunted down every day for a week, but no snow came.' This is a very common expression in the Lakes district of Otago. i cannot remember hearing it in Canterbury, though the job is done often enough.
Notes:  [1918]

